--- TIER 1: HIGHEST FIT (all 4 signature facts explained) ---

CANDIDATE 1: MULTI-STREAM SECOND-STREAM (STATIC VB) BINDING CARRIES UNINITIALIZED DATA
---------------------------------------------------------------------
The multi-stream path (ms_useMultiStreamVertexBuffers=true) binds TWO vertex buffers:
  stream 0: m_dynamicStream (skinned pos+normal[+dot3])
  stream 1: m_staticStream (color + 2D UVs)

When ms_useMultiStreamVertexBuffers=false (runtime default per ConfigClientGraphics default),
the single-stream path copies systemStream (which holds ALL components) into dynamicStream via
`outIt.copy(m_systemStream->beginReadOnly(), ...)` and the static stream is never created.

BUT: the GAP-6 multistream latch log (gap6_latch.log) at install() shows the ACTUAL runtime
value of ms_useMultiStreamVertexBuffers. If this is TRUE at runtime (D3D11 plugin may return
maxStreamCount > 1 + supportsStreamOffsets=true, unlike D3D9's expected false), then:
  - The static stream (StaticVertexBuffer) is only written ONCE at init (fillConstantVertexBufferData).
    The dot3 4D texture set is skipped in fillConstantVertexBufferData (case 4 branch: saves to
    m_sourceDot3Vectors, does NOT write destVertexIt -- CONSULT-30-cursor.out line 88-94).
    That means the 4D-TEXCOORD slot in the static stream's buffer is NEVER written.
  - The dynamic stream only has pos+normal+optional dot3 (no color, no 2D UVs).
  - The static StaticVertexBuffer is allocated via `new byte[]` -- no guarantee of zero-init.
  - At draw time, the input layout reads from both streams by semantic. The VS may read
    TEXCOORD0 (the 2D UV set) from the static stream's uninitialized 4D slot, or it reads
    DOT3/TANGENT from an unwritten region.

Mechanism: VS reads an unwritten byte range in the static stream -> garbage live.
Why zero on replay: RenderDoc zero-inits all staging/upload buffers on replay (documented behavior
for USAGE_DEFAULT resources captured before first upload).
Why sync-masked: CPU staging reads the DYNAMIC VB (stream 0) which IS clean; nobody probed stream 1.
Why position-clean: position is at offset 0 in the dynamic stream, always written by skinData.

Test: grep gap6_latch.log for "ms_useMultiStreamVertexBuffers=1". If true, add a probe in
SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp _initialize(): log `multiStream` + check
m_staticStream != nullptr. The quick kill-test: set ConfigClientGraphics::getDisableMultiStreamVertexBuffers
to always return true and see if spikes vanish.

Code locations:
  SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp:344 -- multistream latch
  SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp:661-742 -- multistream code path
  SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp:1191-1243 -- constantFormat setup
  SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp:1387-1402 -- static stream creation
  SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp:1646-1707 -- fillConstantVertexBufferData (dot3 skip)
  Direct3d11_VertexBufferVectorData.cpp:101-164 -- multi-stream bind

CANDIDATE 2: STATIC STREAM DOT3 SLOT UNWRITTEN IN SINGLE-STREAM SYSTEMSTREAM INIT
---------------------------------------------------------------------
Even in the single-stream path, m_systemStream is initialized by fillConstantVertexBufferData()
ONCE (SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp:1409-1411), and skinData() is called each frame.
fillConstantVertexBufferData skips the 4D texcoord set (dot3): the case 4 branch extracts to
m_sourceDot3Vectors but does NOT write destVertexIt (SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp:1688-1701).

The dot3 slot in m_systemStream starts uninitialized. skinData with SM_softSkinning calls
fillVertexBuffer, which DOES write the dot3 texcoord set via setTextureCoordinates() -- IF
m_hasDot3Vector is true. But if the garment mesh has no dot3 data (m_hasDot3Vector=false for a
simple robe), the dot3 slot is never written at all. The copy from systemStream to dynamicStream
faithfully copies the uninitialized dot3 bytes.

BUT: if the garment has no dot3, dynamicFormat does not declare a TEXCOORD set for dot3 either,
so the input layout would not have a TEXCOORD slot at that offset -> the VS would not read it.
Unless the input layout is built from the VS reflection (which may declare a TEXCOORD beyond
what the VB format has), at which point the phantom-zero buffer (slot 15, stride 0) would supply
zeros for that channel -- zero on live too, so this doesn't explain garbage.

HOWEVER: for garments WITH dot3, the systemStream's dot3 bytes start uninitialized and are
overwritten correctly by skinData each frame -- but ONLY if doSkinning=true (every-other-frame
skinning may skip). If everyOtherFrameSkinningEnabled and this frame is the skip frame, skinData
returns early WITHOUT writing anything (SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp:1734-1737), and
the copy picks up whatever was in systemStream from the prior frame -- not guaranteed to be
correct for the CURRENT pose (slightly stale but not garbage). Doesn't explain spikes.

More interesting: the initial state of m_systemStream before the FIRST skin call contains
uninitialized memory (position bytes, normal bytes). On the very first frame of a new NPC,
copy() would copy garbage into the dynamic ring. On replay, RenderDoc zero-inits. Sync-masked:
by the time you CPU-stall to probe the VB, you are past the first frame and the skin has run.
Position-clean: after the first frame, position is always correct (subsequent frames overwrite it).

This explains FIRST-FRAME spikes only, not persistent ones. Lower fit for persistent spikes.

CANDIDATE 3: WRONG RING BUFFER BOUND AT DRAW TIME (SKIN WROTE TO SKIN-RING, DRAW READS MAIN RING)
---------------------------------------------------------------------
The 2026-06-07 code split the ring into two: ms_d3dRingBuffer (main) and ms_d3dSkinRingBuffer.
The routing in lock() is:
  bool isSkin = (vertexSize != 28) && (vertexSize != 24);
  uses ms_d3dSkinRingBuffer if isSkin, else ms_d3dRingBuffer.

The BINDING side (StateCache::setVertexBuffer) calls data->getRingBuffer() which returns
m_ringBuffer (set at lock time) or falls back to ms_d3dRingBuffer.Get() if null.

The VBVectorData::bind() also uses data->getRingBuffer() for the dynamic stream.

Critical race: m_ringBuffer is a RAW POINTER stored on the DynamicVertexBufferData instance.
If lock() is called with vertexSize=48 (skin ring), m_ringBuffer = ms_d3dSkinRingBuffer.Get().
The bind at draw time reads m_ringBuffer. This is correct IF the same instance's lock()
ran first. But what if:
  (a) A body draw (same instance, body dynamicStream with vertexSize=24) runs lock() -> m_ringBuffer = main ring.
  (b) The garment draw (same NPC, different instance, vertexSize=48) runs lock() -> m_ringBuffer = skin ring.
  Each instance has its OWN m_ringBuffer, so there is no cross-contamination between instances.
  This is safe.

BUT: what if the garment dynamicStream's vertexSize is 28 or 24? A robe with ONLY position+normal
and a 2D texcoord (pos=12, norm=12, uv0=8 = 32 bytes, or just pos+norm=24) would route to the
MAIN ring. Then beginFrameSkin() does NOT discard the main ring. If the main ring carries garment
data from a prior frame AND the CuiLayer (UI) does a whole-ring WRITE_DISCARD on the main ring
(because UI VBs have vertexSize=24 or 28 -> isSkin=false -> main ring), then the garment slice
is clobbered mid-frame by UI geometry, and the deferred DrawIndexed reads UI vertex data at the
garment's offset.

Mechanism: UI whole-ring WRITE_DISCARD on the main ring nukes the garment slice -> garbage (UI vert data)
live. RenderDoc replay: WRITE_DISCARD's new backing is zero-initialized on replay. Sync-masked:
staging readback probes the post-discard state (after the CuiLayer discard, the probed bytes are
UI-garbage or zero depending on whether UI wrote to that offset -- and the probe fires BEFORE DrawIndexed,
so it may see the garment's original data before the discard that happens intra-frame). Position-clean:
the probe reads position-at-slice-offset which is the garment's written position, not yet clobbered.
Wait -- if the discard clobbers the slice entirely, the staging readback would also see clobbered data.
This inconsistency reduces fit.

Actually a better framing: the lock() for the garment ran, wrote clean data to offset X on the main
ring. Then a WRITE_DISCARD (new-frame or CuiLayer whole-ring lock) renamed the backing buffer.
The garment's m_ringBuffer still points to the OLD backing (D3D11 DYNAMIC WRITE_DISCARD CONTRACT:
Map(WRITE_DISCARD) returns a new backing allocation; the driver manages the swap atomically for
the GPU). The IASetVertexBuffers at draw time binds ms_currentVBVectorBuffers[0] = the CURRENT
ms_d3dRingBuffer.Get() (or ms_d3dSkinRingBuffer.Get()) -- NOT the stale old backing.

Actually the bind uses m_ringBuffer which is the ComPtr::Get() at lock time. After WRITE_DISCARD,
the ID3D11Buffer* object (ms_d3dRingBuffer.Get()) is THE SAME OBJECT -- D3D11 WRITE_DISCARD
doesn't create a new ID3D11Buffer, it internally aliases new memory. So the pointer is stable.
The danger is only if WRITE_DISCARD overwrites the garment's offset in the same frame:
  - If garment locks at offset X, then a later WRITE_DISCARD (ringUsed=0), then a UI lock writes
    at offset 0 of the NEW generation which physically overlaps the garment's offset X in the
    NEW generation backing. DrawIndexed reads offset X from the NEW generation -> UI garbage.

This is the intra-frame WRITE_DISCARD overwrite hazard. It was supposedly tested by P19_DISCARD_ONLY
(every lock gets WRITE_DISCARD) and found to show NO CHANGE -- but P19_DISCARD_ONLY operated on the
SAME ring (before the ring split), not the dedicated skin ring. The skin-ring split changes the
equation: the skin ring only DISCARDS once per beginFrameSkin (once per frame, not per-lock).
The question is whether any OTHER lock ever triggers a DISCARD on the skin ring mid-frame.

The DISCARD condition in lock() for the skin ring:
  if (skinNewFrame || forceDiscard || skinUsed + length > skinSize)
The 16MB skin ring is sized to avoid wrap-mid-frame. skinNewFrame=true only at beginFrameSkin
(once/frame). So the skin ring should NOT discard mid-frame under normal conditions.

FOR THE MAIN RING: CuiLayer's whole-ring lock does:
  getNumberOfLockableDynamicVertices(withDiscard=true) -> returns ms_size / vertexSize (the full ring)
  lock(full_ring_size) -> length = full_ring_size * vertexSize = ms_size bytes
                         -> triggers WRITE_DISCARD (since the full ring won't fit in remaining space, or ringNewFrame).
If a garment's dynamicStream has vertexSize=24 or 28 (routed to main ring), this CuiLayer discard
CLOBBERS it. This is the highest-fit mechanism for clobbering.

Test: log isSkin for each SBSSP dynamicStream lock. Find garments with vertexSize=24 or 28.
Code location: Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:268 (`isSkin` discriminator).

CANDIDATE 4: PHANTOM-ZERO BUFFER AT SLOT 15 READ INSTEAD OF ACTUAL STREAM
---------------------------------------------------------------------
The input layout in D3D11 may declare elements with InputSlot=15, stride=0 (phantom zero buffer).
This is used for VS-declared inputs that the VBFormat doesn't cover (Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp:1254-1267).
For the garment VS (e.g. a_specmap_bump variant), if the VS declares a TEXCOORD beyond what the
dynamic stream's VertexBufferFormat has, the phantom element at slot 15 returns 0 for that
component on replay AND on live. But position is in slot 0 (the actual VB). So this is NOT
garbage on live -- it's always 0. Doesn't fit the "garbage live" signature. Low fit.

CANDIDATE 5: INPUT LAYOUT STRIDE/OFFSET MISMATCH FOR THE MULTI-STREAM VECTOR PATH
---------------------------------------------------------------------
The multi-stream bind (VertexBufferVectorData::bind) extracts strides from each stream:
  strides[stream] = static_cast<UINT>(data->getVertexSize())
  offsets[stream] = static_cast<UINT>(data->getOffset()) * strides[stream]  (for dynamic stream)
  offsets[stream] = 0  (for static stream)

The input layout in Direct3d11_VertexDeclarationMap::getOrCreateMultiStream() maps semantics to
streams based on what each VertexBufferFormat declares. If the static stream declares COLOR0 +
TEXCOORD0 (2D UV), and the dynamic stream declares POSITION + NORMAL + TEXCOORD0 (4D dot3),
the input layout must map TEXCOORD0 to slot 0 (dynamic) for the dot3 set AND TEXCOORD1 to
slot 1 (static) for the 2D UV. If the semantic index remapping is wrong (e.g. the layout maps
TEXCOORD0 to the static stream's COLOR0 bytes) -> wrong data live.

Mechanism: semantic-index collisions between static (UV at TEXCOORD0) and dynamic (dot3 at TEXCOORD0)
streams cause the IA to read from the wrong slot/offset. D3D9 avoids this by separate SetStreamSource
per stream; D3D11 requires careful TEXCOORD0/TEXCOORD1 partitioning across InputSlot values.
If the VS reads POSITION from TEXCOORD0 (wrong semantic) -> garbage.

Actually POSITION is always declared as POSITION, so the VS cannot confuse POSITION with TEXCOORD.
More plausible: the VS reads a TEXCOORD at a register that the layout maps to the WRONG stream
or wrong offset -> garbage live. RenderDoc replay: replay re-executes IA with the same layout;
if the layout is wrong, replay should ALSO be wrong. Unless RenderDoc fixes up or zero-inits the
unbound slots. Zero-on-replay requires a zero-init of something. If the static stream
(StaticVertexBuffer, USAGE_DEFAULT) was never written to GPU (just CPU-side locked and filled once
at init) and RenderDoc zero-inits DEFAULT resources not captured in a copy, then live it has
uninitialized GPU memory (static VB upload might have landed garbage bytes from the CPU
new byte[] allocation), and replay shows zeros.

This is a strong candidate IF ms_useMultiStreamVertexBuffers=true at runtime.

Test: Check if Direct3d11_VertexDeclarationMap::getOrCreateMultiStream correctly partitions
TEXCOORD indices between static and dynamic streams.

CANDIDATE 6: INDEX BUFFER REFERENCING VERTICES PAST THE LOCKED COUNT (TRI-STRIP PATH ONLY)
---------------------------------------------------------------------
The CONSULT-29-B (cursor) identified that tri-strip indices use raw getTriStripVertexIndex()
while m_vertexCount is the COMPACTED count. A strip can have raw index > m_vertexCount-1.
The cape-strip-probe (StateCache.cpp:3462-3555) was added to catch this.

But the prompt says tri-strips are DORMANT. However "dormant" may mean not the primary path --
if ANY strip render command exists in a garment's m_renderCommands, drawPartialIndexedTriangleStrip
fires. If the garment has even one tri-strip (alongside tri-lists), the strip's raw indices can
exceed m_vertexCount -> DrawIndexed fetches past the locked slice -> garbage (uninitialized ring
tail) live -> zero on replay.

Mechanism: lock(m_vertexCount) writes verts [0, m_vertexCount). A strip index of, say, 2630
(actual example from the handoff comment at SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp:1592)
causes the VS to fetch vertex 2630 which is past the locked slice -> ring memory for a DIFFERENT
draw or the fresh-discard tail -> garbage.

This fits ALL four facts:
  - Garbage live: post-slice ring memory is stale from prior draw or fresh undefined.
  - Zero on replay: RenderDoc zero-inits undefined ring memory.
  - Sync-masked (mostly): staging readback of position at [0, m_vertexCount) is CLEAN;
    the out-of-bounds read is at a DIFFERENT index, not probed.
  - Position-clean: the probe checks verts [0, numberOfVertices) which are correctly written.
    The spiking vertices are those accessed via out-of-bounds strip indices.
  - Body draws clean: body tri-lists have in-range indices (cape-index-probe confirmed).
  - D3D9: D3D9 uses SetStreamSource with byteOffset per instance AND DrawIndexedPrimitive
    with BaseVertexIndex which shifts the index -> the raw strip index 2630 is interpreted
    as an offset FROM BaseVertexIndex, landing within the correct per-character VB segment.
    In D3D11, the IASetVertexBuffers offset IS the base; DrawIndexed BaseVertexLocation is 0.
    So index 2630 in D3D11 reaches 2630*stride bytes past the start of the buffer (the skin ring
    offset + 2630*stride), which lands well past the lock(m_vertexCount) slice.
  - Why NOT killed by DISCARD_ONLY: DISCARD_ONLY renamed the ring but the out-of-bounds read
    still fetches from the new allocation's uninitialized tail -> still garbage.

Wait: DISCARD_ONLY result was "NO CHANGE" per the comments. If strip out-of-bounds caused spikes,
DISCARD_ONLY would STILL produce spikes (garbage tail after the locked slice) or FEWER spikes
(zeros in the fresh allocation -> zero-position spikes = degenerate/collapsed not RADIATING).
The "NO CHANGE" under DISCARD_ONLY could mean either (a) this is not the cause, or (b) the fresh
allocation has initialized-to-garbage memory from the allocator (WRITE_DISCARD doesn't zero the
buffer on live, only on replay).

The cape-strip-probe was recently ADDED (2026-06-07). Its output will distinguish this.

Test: Read cape-strip-probe.txt if it exists. If it shows readPast=1 on strip draws, this is confirmed.
Code: SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp:1589-1634 (index probe, but only for the VBVector path).
      Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp:3462-3555 (strip staging readback).

CANDIDATE 7: VERTEX FORMAT STRIDE MISMATCH BETWEEN LOCK SIDE AND INPUT LAYOUT SIDE
---------------------------------------------------------------------
The `getVertexSize()` returned by DynamicVertexBufferData (from VertexBufferDescriptor) is used
both to compute the lock slice size AND the IASetVertexBuffers stride.

The VertexBufferDescriptor is built from the VertexBufferFormat in Direct3d11_VertexBufferDescriptorMap.
The Input Layout elements in D3D11 must use the SAME stride as the bound VB.

If the D3D11 input layout for the garment VS was created when the VBFormat had FEWER components
(e.g., a TEXCOORD set was added or removed due to LOD switching), but the cached InputLayout
still uses the old stride, then IASetVertexBuffers supplies stride=48 but the layout was compiled
for stride=32 -> each vertex the VS reads is offset by (48-32)=16 bytes from where the engine
wrote it -> garbage.

Mechanism: stale input layout cache with wrong stride for the actual VBFormat.
Why garbage live: the VS reads component at wrong offset -> stale ring bytes.
Why zero replay: RenderDoc zero-inits new allocations.
Why sync-masked: the probe checks position at byte offset 0, which is always correct (position
is always the first field at offset 0 regardless of stride). The stride mismatch shifts LATER
reads (normal, UV) but the probe only reads the first 3 floats.

Test: log the stride values in IASetVertexBuffers vs the VBFormat's expected vertexSize for
garment draws. Code: Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp:1237-1253 (IASetVertexBuffers call).
Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:261 (vertexSize = m_vertexBufferDescriptor.vertexSize).

CANDIDATE 8: CBUFFER TAIL READ AS VS POSITION INPUT (SPECULATIVE / CREATIVE)
---------------------------------------------------------------------
The VS slot 0 cbuffer has 72 float4 registers (1152 bytes). If the composeSlot0Shadow fails to
mark s_slot0Dirty before the deferred DrawIndexed for a garment (e.g., setObjectToWorldTransformAndScale
ran for a BODY draw and set s_anyMatrixWritten, but the GARMENT draw comes later and the world
matrix is now for a different object), the GARMENT draw gets a cbuffer with the PREVIOUS object's
world matrix -> the garment vertices are transformed by the wrong WVP -> spike to wrong position.

But this is a cbuffer issue not a VB issue. The position data in the VB is correct (confirmed by probe).
The spike would result from the VS applying a WVP that places the vertex far off screen. This would
show as spikes to CONSISTENT positions (determined by the wrong WVP) not random garbage. And it would
affect body draws too if they had the wrong WVP. Body draws are clean -> WVP is object-correct.

Additionally, for garments specifically: prepareToDraw() for SBSSP calls
  Graphics::setObjectToWorldTransformAndScale(transform_apw, Vector::xyz111)
which calls setObjectToWorldTransformAndScale_impl -> composeSlot0Shadow() -> s_slot0Dirty=true.
The garment SBSSP owns its own prepareToDraw, so the WVP is composed for the garment's transform.
Low fit -- the garment is a separate SBSSP instance with its own prepareToDraw.

