CANDIDATE 10: EVERY-OTHER-FRAME SKINNING SKIP ON THE GARMENT SBSSP
---------------------------------------------------------------------
If m_everyOtherFrameSkinningEnabled=true for the garment primitive, and this frame is the SKIP
frame, skinData returns early WITHOUT writing position/normal (SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp:1734).
The systemStream is NOT re-skinned. The copy() then copies the PREVIOUS FRAME's systemStream data
into the dynamic ring. This is stale (T-1 pose) but not garbage -- it would cause one-frame lag
pose jitter, not spikes to infinity.

UNLESS m_hasBeenSkinned=false on the first frame AND doSkinning check is wrong -> systemStream
contains uninitialized bytes from the `new byte[]` allocation (no memset for the vertex data
portion, only the source data block at line 1316: `memset(m_sourceData, 0, alloc_size)` -- but
m_systemStream is NOT m_sourceData). SystemVertexBuffer is allocated as a raw new[] array
(SystemVertexBuffer.h) which is NOT zero-initialized.

Mechanism for first-frame-only: systemStream contains uninitialized heap memory; first copy()
sends garbage to ring -> spike on first render. Subsequent frames: skinData fills systemStream
correctly; copy() sends good data. But sync-masked: by the time a user noticing spikes does a
CPU probe, the garment has rendered many frames correctly.

If garments FREQUENTLY spawn (new NPCs appearing, costume changes), first-frame spikes would be
persistent-looking. This fits the "NPC garment-only" pattern well.

Test: Add a probe in prepareToDraw() that detects m_hasBeenSkinned==false and logs it.
After the first skin call in skinData (SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp:1714), m_hasBeenSkinned
is set to true. Zero-on-replay: RenderDoc captures the frame AFTER the ring has been written; the
first-frame spike frame may not be captured because RenderDoc capture is manual.

CANDIDATE 11: INTRA-FRAME WRITE_NO_OVERWRITE RACE BETWEEN SKIN-RING WRITE AND A DIFFERENT
GARMENT'S BEGINFRAMESKIN RESET (TIMING WINDOW IN THE DEDICATED RING)
---------------------------------------------------------------------
beginFrameSkin() sets ms_skinNewFrame=true (DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:168-173). This causes the
NEXT lock() for ANY isSkin VB to do WRITE_DISCARD. If two garment primitives are rendered in
the same frame:
  - Garment A: lock() with ms_skinNewFrame=true -> WRITE_DISCARD, write A's data at offset 0.
  - Garment B: lock() with ms_skinNewFrame=false -> WRITE_NO_OVERWRITE, write B's data at offset X.
  - DRAW for A comes (deferred after prepareToDraw runs for ALL visible objects? Or interleaved?).

If the engine's render loop interleaves prepareToDraw and draw() at the ShaderPrimitiveSorter
level (prepare all, then draw all), then:
  - All garments prepareToDraw (lock + write) in sequence
  - All garments draw() in sequence after that
This is the SAFE pattern. No race.

But if prepareToDraw and draw() are interleaved per-primitive (prepare A, draw A, prepare B, draw B...):
  - Prepare A: lock DISCARD at 0, write, unlock. A's m_offset=0.
  - DRAW A: binds at offset 0. FINE.
  - Prepare B: lock NO_OVERWRITE at offsetX, write, unlock. B's m_offset=offsetX.
  - DRAW B: binds at offsetX. FINE.
No race in this case either.

The race only emerges if beginFrameSkin() fires MID-FRAME (between two garment draws):
  - Garment A: prepare (lock DISCARD at 0), draw (reads offset 0). Fine.
  - beginFrameSkin() is called AGAIN mid-frame (this should not happen -- it's called ONCE before
    beginScene per the implementation comment).

Low fit -- beginFrameSkin is documented as once-per-frame. Unless it fires multiple times
(multi-pass rendering: StaticShaderData::apply per pass?). Check if beginFrameSkin is accidentally
called per-PASS rather than per-FRAME.

CANDIDATE 12: VS READS AN UNWRITTEN NORMAL COMPONENT THAT PARTICIPATES IN POSITION COMPUTATION
---------------------------------------------------------------------
Standard skeletal VSes do NOT use normals to compute SV_Position. They use only vertex POSITION
and the WVP matrix. HOWEVER: some SWG vertex shaders (especially specular-bump variants) have
complex HLSL that might use normal data in an intermediate computation whose result feeds into
the position transform indirectly (e.g., morph target, displacement, dot3 offset).

If a garment VS uses the NORMAL field in a position computation (unusual but not impossible for
older SWG VSes), and the normal bytes happen to be garbage (e.g., first frame before skinData
writes them), this would cause geometric spikes.

Mechanism: garment-specific VS reads normal bytes as a position offset -> garbage normal -> spike.
Why clean on body draws: body uses a different VS (no such displacement term).
Why zero on replay: RenderDoc zero-inits.
Why sync-masked: probe reads position at offset 0 only.

Test: inspect the compiled HLSL for the garment-specific VSes (a_specmap_bump_vs20_for_ps20.vsh
family) to see if any intermediate computation affects SV_Position using a per-vertex input other
than POSITION.

CANDIDATE 13: VERTEX BUFFER OBJECT POINTER STALE AFTER COM RESOURCE DESTRUCTION/RECREATE
---------------------------------------------------------------------
If the skin ring ComPtr (ms_d3dSkinRingBuffer) is ever Reset() and re-created mid-session
(e.g., on device lost/reset, though unlikely in D3D11), then old ID3D11Buffer* pointers cached
in m_ringBuffer on existing SBSSP instances become dangling. The draw binds the dangling pointer.
D3D11 would accept a dangling COM pointer silently and return garbage data.

RenderDoc intercepts all COM calls; it may substitute a zero-initialized buffer for the dangling
resource during replay. Sync-masked: CPU doesn't touch the D3D11 buffer pointer.

Low fit -- D3D11 device loss is uncommon and the ring is only created once at install().

CANDIDATE 14: VERTEX BUFFER BINDING USES ms_currentVBVectorBuffers[0] WHICH IS THE OLD SKIN-RING
POINTER BEFORE THE 2026-06-07 RING SPLIT, WHILE lock() WROTE TO THE NEW SKIN RING
---------------------------------------------------------------------
After the dedicated skin ring was added (2026-06-07), the bind path for the vector route uses:
  buffers[stream] = data->getRingBuffer()
which returns m_ringBuffer (set during lock() to whichever ring was used). This was recently added.

If there is a code path where m_ringBuffer is NOT set (e.g., the garment was constructed before
the split was live, m_ringBuffer initialized to nullptr in the constructor), then getRingBuffer()
falls back to ms_d3dRingBuffer.Get() (the MAIN ring). But the data was written to the skin ring.
The draw then reads from the MAIN ring at the garment's offset -- which contains whatever main-ring
data was there (UI geometry, other draws) -> garbage live.

Code: Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.h:134-138 (getRingBuffer() fallback to ms_d3dRingBuffer).
The fallback fires only if m_ringBuffer==nullptr. m_ringBuffer is initialized to nullptr in the
constructor (DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:225), and set in lock() (line 332: `m_ringBuffer = ringBuffer`).
If lock() was never called (brand new primitive before first prepareToDraw), m_ringBuffer is null and
getRingBuffer() returns the main ring. But bind() is only called AFTER prepareToDraw (which calls lock()).
So m_ringBuffer should always be set by the time bind() fires.

Unless there is a path where setVertexBufferVector fires BEFORE the first lock() on a garment --
e.g., if the engine binds the VBVector to set up state but doesn't call prepareToDraw first. This
seems unlikely but is worth verifying.

CANDIDATE 15: RENDERDOC CAPTURES THE FRAME IN A ZEROED STATE (SMALL SPIKES ON REPLAY)
---------------------------------------------------------------------
The prompt notes "nearly clean (only small spikes)" on replay, not perfectly clean. This suggests
the zero-init hypothesis for some spikes but not all. Small spikes on replay could mean:
  - Some vertices are fetched from zero-initialized memory (the undefined region), causing them
    to be at position (0,0,0) in object space, which after WVP lands at the character's world
    origin (NOT infinity). These appear as "small spikes" to a nearby point.
  - Large spikes live are caused by STALE data (prior draw's geometry, unrelated numbers) rather
    than zeros.

This reframes the problem: the undefined memory on replay is 0 -> small spike to origin.
Live, the undefined memory is whatever was in the ring before (other draw's vertices, or driver
heap content) -> large spike to wherever those floats happen to point.

This supports the INDEX-OUT-OF-BOUNDS class (candidate 6) or the MULTI-STREAM-STATIC-STREAM
uninitialized class (candidate 1). The "small" replay spikes are the zero-initialized counterpart.

==========================================================
RANKING (best fit first, considering ALL four signature facts)
==========================================================

RANK 1: CANDIDATE 6 — TRI-STRIP INDEX READ-PAST m_vertexCount
  Score: 4/4 facts. Garment-only. D3D9 safe (D3D9's BaseVertexIndex makes raw indices relative).
  D3D11: DrawIndexed(count, startIndex, baseVertexLocation=0) + IASetVertexBuffers offset bakes
  the base. Raw strip index > m_vertexCount fetches past the locked slice. Position-clean: the
  CPU probe scans [0, m_vertexCount) which is written. Zero-on-replay: undefined ring tail is
  zero on RenderDoc replay. Sync-masked: probe covers only written region.
  The cape-strip-probe (StateCache.cpp:3462) was just added; its output will confirm or kill this.
  ONE-SHOT TEST: read cape-strip-probe.txt. If readPast=1 on strip draws, confirmed.

RANK 2: CANDIDATE 1 — MULTI-STREAM SECOND STREAM CARRIES UNINITIALIZED DATA
  Score: 4/4 facts IF ms_useMultiStreamVertexBuffers=true at runtime.
  The GAP-6 log shows the exact runtime value. If true:
    - Static stream created with `new byte[]` (no zero-init for StaticVertexBuffer backing)
    - fillConstantVertexBufferData skips 4D dot3 slot -> those bytes are never written to static VB
    - VS reads TEXCOORD from static stream at an uninitialized offset -> garbage live
    - Zero on replay: D3D11 USAGE_DEFAULT static VBs initialized to GPU-undefined; RenderDoc
      captures the UPLOAD call and replays with the CPU data, which IS zero for the unwritten dot3 slot
  ONE-SHOT TEST: check gap6_latch.log for ms_useMultiStreamVertexBuffers=1.

RANK 3: CANDIDATE 10 — FIRST-FRAME SYSTEMSTREAM UNINITIALIZED (FREQUENT SPAWN PATTERN)
  Score: 3/4 (explains persistent-appearing spikes if NPCs spawn frequently; less clean for
  existing stable NPCs). SystemVertexBuffer is `new byte[]` (no memset). First call to copy()
  sends uninitialized heap bytes to the ring. Position probe is clean because the probe runs
  on SUBSEQUENT frames after skinData has run.
  ONE-SHOT TEST: add m_hasBeenSkinned probe in prepareToDraw before lock(); if spikes correlate
  with first-skin frames, confirmed. Also: memset the systemStream in SystemVertexBuffer ctor
  as a fixability test (should eliminate spikes if this is the cause).

RANK 4: CANDIDATE 3 — GARMENT VERTEXSIZE=24/28 ROUTED TO MAIN RING, CLOBBERED BY UI DISCARD
  Score: 3.5/4. The routing discriminator `(vertexSize != 28) && (vertexSize != 24)` means any
  garment with vertexSize 24 or 28 goes to the MAIN ring. CuiLayer whole-ring locks on the main
  ring do WRITE_DISCARD -> clobber. Position-clean: the probe fires BEFORE the CuiLayer lock
  that clobbers it -- but actually: if the staging readback (Map READ) fires BEFORE DrawIndexed
  and AFTER the write, and the CuiLayer discard happens between write and DrawIndexed, then
  the probe might MISS the clobber (it reads the pre-clobber state). This is frame-rate sensitive.
  The dedicated skin ring was added 2026-06-07 specifically to test this -- the question is
  whether ALL spiking garments have vertexSize outside {24,28}.
  ONE-SHOT TEST: log isSkin + vertexSize for all garment SBSSP locks.

RANK 5: CANDIDATE 7 — INPUT LAYOUT STRIDE MISMATCH (CACHED LAYOUT WITH WRONG STRIDE)
  Score: 3/4. Explains garbage for non-position components; position at offset 0 always correct.
  The VertexDeclarationMap cache uses VBFormat as key; if VBFormat changes between LOD switch
  and the cache gets the old layout, stride is wrong. Less likely given the input layout cache
  uses the full VBFormat as a key.

RANK 6: CANDIDATE 5 — MULTI-STREAM SEMANTIC-INDEX COLLISION IN INPUT LAYOUT CREATION
  Score: 3/4 IF multistream is active. TEXCOORD0 collision between static and dynamic streams
  could cause the IA to read from the wrong stream's bytes.

RANK 7: CANDIDATE 14 — m_ringBuffer STALE NULL FALLBACK TO MAIN RING POST RING-SPLIT
  Score: 3/4. Newly introduced risk with 2026-06-07 ring split. m_ringBuffer=null fallback
  returns main ring when skin-ring data was written there -> main-ring reads garbage.
  ONE-SHOT TEST: add assert/log if m_ringBuffer==nullptr at getRingBuffer() call time.

RANK 8-15: Candidates 2, 4, 8, 9, 11, 12, 13 have lower fit (1-2 of 4 facts) or are
effectively ruled out by prior experiments.

==========================================================
ONE-SHOT TESTS ORDERED BY SPEED AND SIGNAL
==========================================================

T1 (seconds): Check gap6_latch.log in stage/ -> ms_useMultiStreamVertexBuffers=0 or 1.
  If 1: CANDIDATE 1 is live. If 0: CANDIDATE 1 is dead, jump to T2.

T2 (seconds): Read cape-strip-probe.txt in stage/ (added 2026-06-07).
  If readPast=1 on any strip draw: CANDIDATE 6 confirmed.
  If empty or all ok: CANDIDATE 6 is dead for tri-strips; garment may only have tri-lists.

T3 (code change, 1 build): In DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:lock(), add:
    if (!isSkin && vertexSize != 24 && vertexSize != 28)
      LOG("unexpected routing: vertexSize=%d not routed to skin ring", vertexSize);
  to catch garments routed to the main ring.
  Also log getOffset() at DrawIndexed time for garment draws.

T4 (code change, 1 build): Memset systemStream backing to known sentinel (0xCD) in
  SystemVertexBuffer constructor. If spikes appear with 0xCD positions -> CANDIDATE 10 confirmed.
  Fix: memset to 0 instead.

T5 (RenderDoc): In the capture of a spiking frame, look at IA input-assembly state for a
  spiking draw: what is the VB buffer, offset, stride? What indices are referenced? Do any
  indices exceed m_vertexCount? This distinguishes index-OOB (candidate 6) from write-path issues.

==========================================================
CONCLUSION
==========================================================

The cleanest lateral insight: the existing staging readbacks (cape-stage-probe.txt,
cape-strip-probe.txt, cape-d3d11-probe.txt) contain the answer RIGHT NOW without any new builds.
Reading those files should immediately discriminate between:
  - "COLLAPSE at the D3D11 write site" -> data corruption before Unmap
  - "COLLAPSE at the draw staging" -> ring was overwritten between write and draw
  - "readPast on strip draws" -> index OOB -> CANDIDATE 6
  - "VB clean at draw" -> transformation/WVP issue (already partially ruled out by body-clean fact)

The most NOVEL (not previously raised) candidate with strong fit: CANDIDATE 14 (m_ringBuffer null
fallback after the 2026-06-07 ring split). The split is fresh code; any garment instance whose
lock() ran BEFORE the split but draw() runs AFTER (impossible since both are per-frame) -- actually
more likely: any garment whose DynamicVertexBufferData was constructed but not yet lock()ed could
return the wrong ring. In practice, lock always precedes bind in the same prepareToDraw, so this
is low risk but the null-fallback assert is a zero-cost safety net.

The HIGHEST PROBABILITY candidate given the constraint that "the staging readback of position is
clean" (which means the draw IS reading the correct slice but fetching FROM CORRECT OFFSET) is:
  Candidate 6 (index OOB on strips) or Candidate 7 (stride mismatch makes some vertices point
  to wrong ring bytes). The CONSULT-30 under-write test (DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:347-349:
  memset slice to 0 before write) is already in the code -- its result determines if "draw reads
  past the written slice" (spikes shrink -> zeros) vs "data is corrupted within the slice" (no change).
